1
00:00:01,853 --> 00:00:14,449
Tonight I want to talk about the Mahasi meditation technique, where it came from, what qualities it develops, special features of the technique, some pitfalls we can fall into.

2
00:00:16,593 --> 00:00:21,559
This Mahasi technique is a particular approach to Vipassana or insight meditation.

3
00:00:22,841 --> 00:00:30,071
It's the form of meditation the Buddha adopted when he realized that none of the spiritual techniques he'd already learned were working for him.

4
00:00:31,333 --> 00:00:40,987
His spiritual journey had followed from what we would now call a midlife crisis, when he was suddenly exposed to the reality of sickness, ageing and death.

5
00:00:42,529 --> 00:00:52,262
This had started a period of intense suffering, enough to drive him away from his comfortable home and happy marriage, to take up the life of a wandering ascetic.

6
00:00:54,030 --> 00:01:00,738
Over the following years, he tried two different approaches to spiritual training which were being practiced in his day.

7
00:01:02,040 --> 00:01:08,007
One developed transcendent meditation states, while the other was based on very austere asceticism.

8
00:01:09,670 --> 00:01:17,980
When he saw that neither of these were answering his need to make sense of life, he realized he would have to find his own spiritual path.

9
00:01:19,816 --> 00:01:29,078
The transcendent meditation had cultivated happy, peaceful mental states, while the ascetic training had invited hardship and suffering.

10
00:01:30,963 --> 00:01:36,036
He decided to steer a course between these two extremes, a middle way.

11
00:01:37,382 --> 00:01:40,266
he wouldn't see either happiness or suffering as the goal.

12
00:01:40,286 --> 00:01:51,257
The goal was to find a way to stop the suffering he felt from the knowledge that sickness, ageing and death were in store for himself and for everyone he loved.

13
00:01:53,859 --> 00:02:01,347
A memory came back of an incident in his childhood, where it be he had been watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

14
00:02:02,087 --> 00:02:12,442
He had been alert and curious, happy to be watching all the details of the ceremony, and also peaceful, at ease, not hoping for anything special to happen.

15
00:02:14,145 --> 00:02:17,949
He now recognized the spiritual potential of that mental state.

16
00:02:19,491 --> 00:02:30,728
If there was a way to live peacefully with the knowledge of death, his intuition told him that this combination of alert curiosity and relaxed attention would lead him there.

17
00:02:31,703 --> 00:02:35,709
he sensed his own potential to learn how to stop suffering.

18
00:02:38,431 --> 00:02:59,921
While as a child he had been absorbed by watching what was happening around him, he realised he could turn that focus inward, become absorbed by watching his own moment-to-moment experience, his physical experience of sitting, breathing, walking, as well as his mental experience of thoughts and emotions.

19
00:03:00,812 --> 00:03:07,681
This is what we now term Vipassana or insight meditation, also known as mindfulness meditation.

20
00:03:09,844 --> 00:03:25,925
We can imagine the Buddha was going through various shades of grief and depression because of his acute apprehension of mortality and probably also a desperate anxiety to find a way forward, not unlike our predicament much of the time.

21
00:03:27,795 --> 00:03:37,391
The insight that followed his childhood memory gave him the clue that the way through all these conflicting emotions was to observe them in Vipassana.

22
00:03:39,435 --> 00:03:50,614
The traditional story goes that once he made this determination to follow the middle way between joy and pain, it only took him six hours to reach the fully enlightened state.

23
00:03:51,521 --> 00:04:04,754
When he afterwards started teaching others how to follow in his footsteps, he described his understanding in terms of four truths he had learned along the way, which we now know as the Four Noble Truths.

24
00:04:06,997 --> 00:04:14,445
First was the truth of dukkha, usually translated as suffering, but better as unsatisfactoriness.

25
00:04:15,647 --> 00:04:24,117
He had detected this dukkha in all experience, not only in grief, depression and so on, but also in states of happiness and joy.

26
00:04:24,158 --> 00:04:35,771
When we examine these mindfully, we notice a subtle anxiety associated with the knowledge that these beautiful states are fragile and easily fade away.

27
00:04:36,511 --> 00:04:42,302
Usually we leap to conclusions here, blame ourselves, blame others, blame circumstances.

28
00:04:43,305 --> 00:04:51,000
But the Buddha's careful observation led him to conclude that blame only confused the issue, compounded the pain.

29
00:04:52,021 --> 00:04:57,473
The underlying reality was simply that the beautiful states of happiness and joy had faded.

30
00:04:59,814 --> 00:05:11,130
Probing deep into his experience of body and mind, the Buddha had come to understand that it was all by nature unstable, uncontrollable and therefore unsatisfactory.

31
00:05:13,052 --> 00:05:19,021
Sounds like a discovery that would lead to even deeper depression, despair and maybe even suicide.

32
00:05:20,163 --> 00:05:28,675
But that original intuition that this method of meditation could lead him to the end of suffering proved stronger than any such temptations.

33
00:05:30,680 --> 00:05:44,634
We can imagine him relaxing, becoming so sensitive to his experience that he could say, this here is the feeling of depression, and this slight pushing on the edge of it, this is the desire to get rid of depression.

34
00:05:45,995 --> 00:05:54,105
And to his amazement, no doubt, he found that what was really hurting was not the depression itself, but the desire to be rid of it.

35
00:05:55,603 --> 00:06:02,055
and then, seeing that he could, for a moment at least, relax, let go of that desire.

36
00:06:03,317 --> 00:06:06,262
And with that, the depression became bearable.

37
00:06:09,048 --> 00:06:14,398
You can imagine that that discovery lifted his heart, gave him a shot of joy.

38
00:06:14,898 --> 00:06:18,625
So then he notices, this here is the feeling of joy.

39
00:06:19,194 --> 00:06:26,747
And this slight pulling on the edge of it is the desire to possess the joy, prolong it, become forever joyful.

40
00:06:28,149 --> 00:06:34,740
And while the joy itself is lovely, the desire to own it, prolong it, become it, is stressful.

41
00:06:36,204 --> 00:06:50,398
Thus, tracking his own experience, he was able to convince himself that desire was causing suffering, whether it was the desire to be rid of unpleasant stuff, like depression, or the desire to get more of the pleasant stuff, like joy.

42
00:06:51,899 --> 00:06:54,862
This he later described as the second noble truth.

43
00:06:56,043 --> 00:06:57,785
Desire is the cause of suffering.

44
00:07:00,728 --> 00:07:02,769
And then came the real breakthrough.

45
00:07:04,353 --> 00:07:15,586
As he continued to watch desire with calm, curious attention, feeling the suffering it caused, he was drawn ever deeper into the roots of his experience.

46
00:07:16,889 --> 00:07:22,976
And there came a moment of profound stillness when all desire naturally faded away.

47
00:07:23,016 --> 00:07:29,365
And with that, all suffering stopped and there was deep peace.

48
00:07:31,706 --> 00:07:37,615
It may have only been momentary because until we're fully enlightened, new desires keep arising.

49
00:07:38,757 --> 00:07:47,250
But luckily for us, he recognized that brief moment when desire faded as an experience of what he had been searching for.

50
00:07:47,310 --> 00:07:52,338
The cessation of suffering, a taste of nibbana.

51
00:07:53,779 --> 00:08:00,329
This he later taught as his third noble truth, that there is an end to suffering.

52
00:08:03,819 --> 00:08:13,809
Although the whole wearying process of wanting this, not wanting that, started up again, he now knew there was a way to work with this deeply ingrained conditioning.

53
00:08:15,050 --> 00:08:25,480
Studying his own emotions, attitudes, thoughts and behaviour in Vipassana, he was able to fine tune his understanding of what caused suffering and what brought it to an end.

54
00:08:27,682 --> 00:08:32,427
This allowed him to work out a practical path that could be followed for spiritual awakening.

55
00:08:33,688 --> 00:08:44,490
He calls this the Noble Eightfold Path and we know this as the Fourth Noble Truth.

56
00:08:44,510 --> 00:08:50,802
There are three sections to the Path, Wisdom, Morality and Meditation Training.

57
00:08:51,610 --> 00:09:03,807
Here we're mainly concerned with the third part, but we're based within the wisdom set by the Buddha in his Dhamma teachings, and having taken the precepts, we're working within a framework of morality.

58
00:09:05,609 --> 00:09:11,998
Following his enlightenment, the Buddha spent the remainder of his life teaching others how to reach the same goal.

59
00:09:13,125 --> 00:09:17,089
But he stressed that words alone could only point in the direction of truth.

60
00:09:18,210 --> 00:09:24,615
Each person has to search for, detect and realise the truth within their own experience.

61
00:09:26,918 --> 00:09:31,322
Thus, we don't have to accept any of the teachings on blind faith.

62
00:09:31,341 --> 00:09:36,426
We don't have to think of ourselves as Buddhist or even believe in the historic figure of the Buddha.

63
00:09:37,527 --> 00:09:43,032
We can experiment with the Dhamma, see if these teachings prove a useful guide in our lives.

64
00:09:46,032 --> 00:09:53,864
The motive inspiring our practice can thus be to ask whether the Dhamma is really true, manifesting right here and now in my life.

65
00:09:55,225 --> 00:10:03,359
We answer the question by practicing Vipassana, examining our experience with a calm, curious, attentive observation.

66
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:07,585
But we don't want to get too far ahead of ourselves.

67
00:10:09,488 --> 00:10:11,634
Remember that we're on a training course here.

68
00:10:12,054 --> 00:10:14,861
We're not expecting full enlightenment.

69
00:10:14,881 --> 00:10:19,553
That's a very worthy long-term goal for meditation practice.

70
00:10:19,573 --> 00:10:23,464
But we need to put it aside for now, or else it will get in the way.

71
00:10:24,153 --> 00:10:27,917
Joseph Goldstein gives the analogy of walking home through the woods at night.

72
00:10:28,778 --> 00:10:31,642
He could see the lights of his house ahead in the distance.

73
00:10:31,662 --> 00:10:33,683
That was his goal, to get to the house.

74
00:10:34,565 --> 00:10:39,730
But to make any progress, he had to look down at the ground in front of him, take it one step at a time.

75
00:10:40,631 --> 00:10:43,634
Looking ahead while stepping usually meant a tumble.

76
00:10:46,118 --> 00:10:53,687
In the same way, thoughts about enlightenment or perfect happiness get in the way of the meditation skills we're trying to learn here and now.

77
00:10:54,932 --> 00:11:08,328
So we have to let go of our desires for psychological well-being and spiritual insight and instead focus on learning the technique, trusting that the process will, in its own good time, bring about insight and happiness.

78
00:11:12,113 --> 00:11:16,197
It's best to think of the retreat as essentially a training course.

79
00:11:16,616 --> 00:11:22,345
We're training ourselves in the art of meditation as taught by the Mahasi Sayadaw of Burma.

80
00:11:23,385 --> 00:11:27,971
And like any training you've ever done, it's going to take time and effort and patience.

81
00:11:29,955 --> 00:11:41,190
The Mahasi Sayadaw was a Buddhist monk teaching in a monastery in the north of Burma until in 1948 he was asked to come to Yangon and teach meditation to lay people.

82
00:11:42,587 --> 00:11:56,825
This was an unusual request as it was widely held, in Burma at any rate, that any progress in meditation required a remove from all worldly affairs so as to dedicate one's time fully to spiritual training for many months and years.

83
00:11:57,985 --> 00:12:05,715
This allowed very deeply absorbed states of concentration to develop, known as samatha jhanas.

84
00:12:07,297 --> 00:12:12,222
It was only monastics who had the necessary time and seclusion to master these states.

85
00:12:14,397 --> 00:12:26,043
The training technique that the Mahasi Sayadaw had learned and practiced did not require the deep absorptions, but instead developed what is known as momentary concentration.

86
00:12:27,695 --> 00:12:30,818
It's not that the concentration only lasts for a moment.

87
00:12:31,679 --> 00:12:34,582
It is the same strength of various levels of jhana.

88
00:12:35,683 --> 00:12:45,534
The distinction between the two is that Samatha focuses on one object, for example the breath, whereas Vipassana lets the focus switch between many objects.

89
00:12:46,395 --> 00:12:52,403
One moment we're aware of breathing, the next of hearing, the next of some emotion arising, and so on.

90
00:12:53,615 --> 00:13:00,350
Thus in Vipassana, the deep level of concentration is experienced over many moments of consciousness.

91
00:13:03,577 --> 00:13:05,682
The Mahasi recognised

92
00:13:07,856 --> 00:13:21,393
that people could develop this level of concentration within a relatively short time frame and thus that this meditation technique was ideally suited for lay people who could perhaps only make a retreat of a few weeks at the most.

93
00:13:22,835 --> 00:13:35,889
This is in keeping with the fact that one of the most prized of all of the Buddha's teachings the discourse on establishing mindfulness was given in the townland of Kuru to the lay people as well as to the monastics.

94
00:13:37,067 --> 00:13:44,577
The Mahasi technique is based around many of the instructions given in this particular discourse, the Satipatthana Sutta.

95
00:13:47,081 --> 00:13:54,931
While some Vipassana training techniques encourage a broad, open awareness, the Mahasi technique focuses on detail.

96
00:13:56,052 --> 00:14:04,003
In the first place, on the sensations of the abdomen caused by breathing, or else the sensations in the feet caused by walking.

97
00:14:05,620 --> 00:14:13,033
We track these until the mind calms down, becomes interested in present experience.

98
00:14:13,053 --> 00:14:16,581
Then we let whatever calls attention to become the new focus.

99
00:14:17,582 --> 00:14:23,232
It could be a sound, an itching sensation, some discomfort in the body perhaps.

100
00:14:24,716 --> 00:14:27,881
We allow our attention go wherever it is naturally called.

101
00:14:29,110 --> 00:14:35,938
And if nothing in particular calls, we go back to the breath at the abdomen, the feeling of the tummy rising and falling.

102
00:14:37,740 --> 00:14:45,711
This cultivates momentary concentration, where the mind can focus on each little detail of what attracts attention.

103
00:14:49,836 --> 00:14:56,163
There are two other aspects to the Mahasi approach that distinguish it from other forms of vipassana training.

104
00:14:57,460 --> 00:15:02,005
One is noting and making a special effort to note intentions.

105
00:15:03,649 --> 00:15:08,556
Another is slowing down all physical activities to a snail's pace.

106
00:15:12,100 --> 00:15:16,986
Noting involves making a short mental note of what you're experiencing.

107
00:15:18,909 --> 00:15:23,956
When feeling the rising and falling movements of the breath, we note rising.

108
00:15:24,510 --> 00:15:27,820
rising, falling, falling.

109
00:15:29,465 --> 00:15:32,874
That helps draw attention more closely to those sensations.

110
00:15:33,856 --> 00:15:38,789
Whereas if we don't make that mental note, we might be only vaguely aware that we're breathing.

111
00:15:41,706 --> 00:15:55,811
When we make the mental notes rising, falling, we are engaging the perceptual faculty of the mind, the ability to discern one thing from another, knowing red from green, hot from cold and so on.

112
00:15:57,453 --> 00:16:03,985
Perception is a very powerful mental process and a very important aspect of the spiritual path.

113
00:16:05,517 --> 00:16:15,851
When Ananda asked Sariputta why it was that people did not attain liberation, Sariputta told him that it was basically a problem of misperception.

114
00:16:16,793 --> 00:16:25,265
Because we perceive things wrongly, our minds end up in a confused turmoil that obscures the underlying peace of Nibbana.

115
00:16:29,673 --> 00:16:33,398
Perception conditions all our thoughts, words and deeds.

116
00:16:35,284 --> 00:16:42,236
I remember one walking meditation where the person in front of me kept sniffing, every footstep, sniff, sniff.

117
00:16:42,778 --> 00:16:44,159
It was driving me bananas.

118
00:16:45,261 --> 00:16:49,288
I was doing my best to watch the irritation, but the thoughts kept pouring out.

119
00:16:50,030 --> 00:16:52,634
Why doesn't he just blow his nose?

120
00:16:52,615 --> 00:16:56,241
How could anybody be so rude, so inconsiderate?

121
00:16:57,364 --> 00:17:02,592
After several minutes of torture, I saw his hand go into his pocket and pull out a tissue.

122
00:17:03,754 --> 00:17:08,844
I watched with bated breath, heard him blow his nose and gave a deep sigh of relief.

123
00:17:09,925 --> 00:17:13,172
But before he'd even put the tissue away, there was another sniff.

124
00:17:14,873 --> 00:17:18,577
To my own amazement, my response wasn't anger, but compassion.

125
00:17:19,519 --> 00:17:21,321
It was only afterwards on reflection.

126
00:17:22,083 --> 00:17:32,096
I'd realised that what I'd been reacting to was not the sound of sniffing, but my own presumption that this was a thoughtless, inconsiderate person who wasn't polite enough to blow his nose.

127
00:17:33,239 --> 00:17:43,192
The sniff following the nose blow showed me that whatever was causing him to sniff, perhaps he had asthma or an allergy or something, couldn't be fixed by simply blowing his nose.

128
00:17:43,730 --> 00:17:46,797
He wasn't a thoughtless, inconsiderate person after all.

129
00:17:47,739 --> 00:17:51,166
It was such a joy to be relieved of all my fury.

130
00:17:51,227 --> 00:18:00,387
He sniffed away at every footstep till the end of the walking session but it no longer bothered me at all.

131
00:18:00,622 --> 00:18:04,046
Although the sounds were the same, they were heard differently.

132
00:18:05,228 --> 00:18:10,954
The pre-nose blow sniffs were heard within a tumult of indignation and anger.

133
00:18:12,296 --> 00:18:16,421
The post-nose blow ones were heard with relief and compassion.

134
00:18:17,803 --> 00:18:23,490
In fact, I grew fonder of him with every sniff because he had taught me such a valuable Dharma lesson.

135
00:18:28,059 --> 00:18:30,363
There's another point to draw from this incident.

136
00:18:31,464 --> 00:18:37,294
It was the fact that compassion arose spontaneously once I saw that the sniffing was due to illness.

137
00:18:38,336 --> 00:18:44,905
I'm using the word I here, but in fact the thinking mind that I identify with was totally surprised by compassion.

138
00:18:45,767 --> 00:18:48,191
It had expected an even deeper burst of anger.

139
00:18:49,192 --> 00:18:55,721
The thinking mind only slowly unravelled the knot, realised that anger was due to a misperception.

140
00:18:57,288 --> 00:18:59,852
This is an example of intuitive intelligence.

141
00:19:01,035 --> 00:19:05,182
It's in direct contact with reality, in this case the sound of sniffing.

142
00:19:06,624 --> 00:19:15,278
It experiences the sound without presumptions about rudeness and inconsideration, sees that the sniff doesn't connect directly to those angry thoughts.

143
00:19:16,320 --> 00:19:22,451
It doesn't need the convoluted logic of the thinking mind, but understands things in a flash.

144
00:19:24,372 --> 00:19:29,577
The insight that comes from intuitive intelligence is not just intellectual.

145
00:19:31,140 --> 00:19:34,663
When it sees clearly, the heart opens.

146
00:19:36,125 --> 00:19:38,307
Again, this is instantaneous.

147
00:19:39,869 --> 00:19:48,539
By comparison, my thinking mind took several seconds to work out why my attitude had changed from anger to compassion.

148
00:19:51,202 --> 00:19:53,484
Intuitive intelligence is primary.

149
00:19:54,006 --> 00:19:56,188
The thinking mind catches up slowly.

150
00:19:56,208 --> 00:20:06,459
This illustrates why we are taking such pains to train ourselves to become aware of present experience rather than lost in thought.

151
00:20:08,119 --> 00:20:17,430
It's easy for us to dismiss detail like the sensations of the tummy rising as irrelevant, but they're providing the training ground for mindfulness.

152
00:20:18,675 --> 00:20:22,500
Just knowing those sensations is a peak beyond thought.

153
00:20:23,701 --> 00:20:35,031
And slowly we learned to trust in a wordless intelligence that is in direct contact with reality, not influenced by beliefs and presumptions.

154
00:20:38,455 --> 00:20:43,721
It's this level of intelligence that we need for insight into the true nature of reality.

155
00:20:45,122 --> 00:20:47,805
We suffer because of our misperceptions.

156
00:20:48,967 --> 00:20:54,213
For example, we mistake what is transient as enduring, reliable.

157
00:20:56,375 --> 00:20:59,019
Our house, our body, our mobile phone.

158
00:20:59,820 --> 00:21:01,563
We expect them to be there when we need them.

159
00:21:02,403 --> 00:21:03,885
We're distraught when they break down.

160
00:21:05,887 --> 00:21:09,132
That's because we rely on our thinking mind far too much.

161
00:21:11,115 --> 00:21:18,483
At the level of direct experience, a million flashes of colour might pass through the eyes and we think, that's my phone.

162
00:21:19,814 --> 00:21:26,683
The thought gives us a feeling of certainty about those million flashes of colour, which we might not even see anymore.

163
00:21:27,605 --> 00:21:32,553
But we still believe that my phone is there where I saw it a moment ago.

164
00:21:35,256 --> 00:21:44,589
By training ourselves to experience life directly, moment to moment, we start to break down our preconceived notions of reality.

165
00:21:46,222 --> 00:21:50,547
It might be during a very ordinary experience like tracking the feet as we walk.

166
00:21:52,028 --> 00:21:59,954
We might feel the foot touch the floor and realise, gosh, this is totally different to how it felt a moment ago as it moved forward.

167
00:22:02,257 --> 00:22:04,338
At one level, nothing has changed.

168
00:22:05,059 --> 00:22:06,141
We know we're just walking.

169
00:22:07,402 --> 00:22:14,407
But the experience is now being seen through new eyes, with avid interest in each transient sensation.

170
00:22:15,755 --> 00:22:20,840
We feel totally alive, in touch with our bodies, with the environment.

171
00:22:22,603 --> 00:22:29,932
This vibrant perspective may only last a few moments, but it's a genuine insight into the nature of reality.

172
00:22:31,894 --> 00:22:39,163
Each glimpse into a world without the filter of thoughts and conception deepens our faith in the practice.

173
00:22:40,560 --> 00:22:58,063
Slowly, we learn to see, as the Buddha did, that all is transitory, a magic show, and that it's a mistake to believe this magic show can deliver anything but sorrow while we try to hang on to what we like, get rid of what we dislike.

174
00:23:01,907 --> 00:23:16,003
To promote these glimpses of the world unfettered by thoughts and ideas, Vipassana practice trains our attention away from the thinking mind and towards sensory experience.

175
00:23:16,023 --> 00:23:18,807
It's ironic that the noting word itself is a thought.

176
00:23:20,450 --> 00:23:23,393
We're using thought to bring us beyond thought.

177
00:23:24,907 --> 00:23:27,231
Say we were building an observation tower.

178
00:23:28,374 --> 00:23:33,721
We want to be high up in the air, above all houses and trees and whatever else will get in the way of our vision.

179
00:23:34,663 --> 00:23:41,515
We want to be well off the ground, but we build our tower from materials we take from the ground, like wood and steel.

180
00:23:42,636 --> 00:23:48,807
Each time we want to go a bit further up, we need more from the earth to build another step, another floor.

181
00:23:48,787 --> 00:23:56,421
Similarly, the word rising directs attention away for all the thoughts we'd otherwise be getting lost in.

182
00:23:58,204 --> 00:24:00,008
But we're not interested in the noting word.

183
00:24:01,230 --> 00:24:06,339
That would be like going up to the top of the observation tower only to stare at the floor beneath us.

184
00:24:07,602 --> 00:24:10,263
The noting word just serves to direct attention.

185
00:24:11,345 --> 00:24:15,528
What we're really interested in are those sensations in the tummy.

186
00:24:15,548 --> 00:24:19,432
They are our direct contact with sensory reality.

187
00:24:22,935 --> 00:24:32,565
When we're directing the mind using the noting word, we're at the first level of concentration of vipassana, called vitaka in Pali.

188
00:24:34,307 --> 00:24:35,667
We're gathering the mind.

189
00:24:36,913 --> 00:24:41,064
If we can keep doing that throughout the retreat, this is excellent practice.

190
00:24:42,366 --> 00:24:47,800
You may notice that at some moments the mind gets fascinated with its present experience.

191
00:24:47,820 --> 00:24:54,096
We're absolutely riveted by an itching sensation, for example, really want to feel every little tingle.

192
00:24:55,122 --> 00:24:57,444
At that stage, we often forget to note.

193
00:24:58,026 --> 00:24:59,428
And that's fine, there's no need.

194
00:25:00,269 --> 00:25:02,230
The noting has already served its purpose.

195
00:25:03,092 --> 00:25:06,115
We're up in our observation tower, seeing clearly.

196
00:25:06,576 --> 00:25:08,219
We don't need to build any higher.

197
00:25:09,279 --> 00:25:11,442
This is the second level of concentration.

198
00:25:12,724 --> 00:25:20,134
Vichara in Pali An analogy used is a bee among flowers.

199
00:25:21,058 --> 00:25:27,171
The flowers are swaying around in a breeze, so the bee has to track the flower, move around with it.

200
00:25:28,374 --> 00:25:33,904
This is Vitaka, where we're tracking the experience using noting words.

201
00:25:36,810 --> 00:25:41,160
There comes a moment when the bee gets close enough to land on the flower.

202
00:25:41,426 --> 00:25:45,632
Even though the flower is still bobbing around, she no longer has to make any effort.

203
00:25:46,093 --> 00:25:48,174
She's being carried around with the flower.

204
00:25:48,955 --> 00:25:56,224
This is vichara, the second level of concentration, where there is an immediate, direct contact with itchiness.

205
00:25:56,766 --> 00:25:58,567
It's absorbing all your attention.

206
00:26:02,031 --> 00:26:06,877
Don't worry if the noting stops when you get riveted by the direct experience of reality.

207
00:26:08,376 --> 00:26:12,261
but you have to start it again as soon as you lose that level of concentration.

208
00:26:13,604 --> 00:26:15,705
Don't think of the loss as a problem or a failure.

209
00:26:16,366 --> 00:26:17,367
It's the same for the bee.

210
00:26:18,048 --> 00:26:21,933
Once she's sipped the nectar from the flower, she must fly off in search of another.

211
00:26:23,757 --> 00:26:28,863
Similarly, we spend a few moments sipping the nectar of direct experience.

212
00:26:29,824 --> 00:26:31,886
Everything is vivid, fascinating.

213
00:26:33,182 --> 00:26:45,155
then our desire to understand things conceptually gets the better of us and we withdraw into our world of thought again and the itchy sensation may seem fuzzy, distant, confusing.

214
00:26:46,718 --> 00:26:50,741
This is part of the natural process of learning about direct experience.

215
00:26:53,285 --> 00:26:58,250
So long as you don't give in to the desire to think your way to enlightenment, it's not a problem.

216
00:26:58,951 --> 00:27:00,252
It's just the way we learn.

217
00:27:01,903 --> 00:27:08,150
All you need to do is start making the effort to direct the mind again using the noting technique.

218
00:27:10,511 --> 00:27:22,001
Sometimes a note like wondering, wondering allows the mind to space it needs to take in the wonder of that little glimpse beyond thought.

219
00:27:23,564 --> 00:27:29,328
After a while, the itchiness or some other sensation in the body may call attention again.

220
00:27:33,780 --> 00:27:36,844
A couple of common mistakes happen with the noting technique.

221
00:27:37,664 --> 00:27:42,170
Firstly, we can get into knots trying to find exactly the right word.

222
00:27:43,230 --> 00:27:45,394
Is this sensation itching or stinging?

223
00:27:46,095 --> 00:27:48,457
Is this a feeling of anger or frustration?

224
00:27:49,558 --> 00:27:57,487
As soon as you notice you're trying to find the exactly right word, then stop fussing and just use the simplest word that comes to mind.

225
00:27:58,087 --> 00:28:01,711
In fact, the words thinking and feeling cover everything.

226
00:28:02,991 --> 00:28:08,622
The noting word is only to direct the mind towards sensations and feelings, away from thoughts.

227
00:28:10,965 --> 00:28:18,980
If it happens that you can't stop trying to get the right word, try the noting word thinking thinking, because that's what's happening.

228
00:28:19,461 --> 00:28:21,726
You are thinking about what word is best.

229
00:28:23,393 --> 00:28:28,858
Another common mistake is to put too much emphasis on the note as though we're shouting at ourselves.

230
00:28:29,740 --> 00:28:37,548
If this happens, if the note sounds loud, getting in the way of the sensations and feelings, then deliberately soften it.

231
00:28:39,310 --> 00:28:44,176
I've heard the note described as a feather brushing against whatever it's noting.

232
00:28:45,018 --> 00:28:46,278
A very light touch.

233
00:28:50,730 --> 00:28:54,224
Sometimes the sound of the note just won't soften.

234
00:28:55,309 --> 00:28:57,298
We're pounding it out and can't stop.

235
00:28:58,965 --> 00:29:01,388
This is usually a sign of over-effort.

236
00:29:02,411 --> 00:29:07,637
We're so determined to do the practice well that we're getting all frenzied and uptight.

237
00:29:08,779 --> 00:29:12,384
If this happens, relax all effort for a while.

238
00:29:12,424 --> 00:29:21,176
Remind yourself that there's no exam coming up, that any new skill takes a lot of time and patience to learn.

239
00:29:25,240 --> 00:29:33,808
And if the moment you go back to noting that same frenzied pounding starts up, that means that some underlying anxiety has surfaced.

240
00:29:34,529 --> 00:29:39,355
Perhaps you tend to be perfectionist and can't bear to think that you may be making any mistake.

241
00:29:40,756 --> 00:29:42,258
This is actually to be welcomed.

242
00:29:42,958 --> 00:29:47,182
We want to allow our many underlying anxieties to surface in Vipassana.

243
00:29:48,104 --> 00:29:49,345
Learn to recognise them.

244
00:29:50,246 --> 00:29:51,467
Work with them mindfully.

245
00:29:53,303 --> 00:30:03,480
You can note uptight or frustrated or trying to get it right and allow yourself to feel that very experience.

246
00:30:05,222 --> 00:30:10,991
In time, this will show us how to live more patiently with perfectionism.

247
00:30:17,856 --> 00:30:21,182
We can also listen out for any emotional tone in the note.

248
00:30:22,044 --> 00:30:22,765
Is it neutral?

249
00:30:23,826 --> 00:30:25,588
Perhaps it's tense with anger?

250
00:30:26,770 --> 00:30:32,200
If so, we can switch to noting anger instead, curious about the experience of anger.

251
00:30:33,602 --> 00:30:40,894
Thus, the tone of the note can be a very helpful indicator of some buried emotion that we might otherwise miss.

252
00:30:43,809 --> 00:30:44,590
But be careful.

253
00:30:45,311 --> 00:30:51,059
It's very easy to get curious about why we're angry rather than the experience of anger.

254
00:30:52,362 --> 00:30:55,606
To start thinking about the cause is to go down a rabbit hole.

255
00:30:57,128 --> 00:31:00,713
But the moment-to-moment experience can be a revelation.

256
00:31:02,797 --> 00:31:06,663
Sometimes anger simply disappears in a flash when we become aware of it.

257
00:31:07,825 --> 00:31:12,230
Sometimes we have to work at it for a long time before there's any relief.

258
00:31:13,357 --> 00:31:23,991
Like in my sniffing experience, I had been noting anger for a few minutes before that magic moment where the intuitive intelligence darted forth to make sense of it all.

259
00:31:27,876 --> 00:31:33,505
This also illustrates how the intuitive intelligence is working away even in a bout of anger.

260
00:31:35,267 --> 00:31:37,029
It doesn't matter what we're aware of.

261
00:31:37,830 --> 00:31:39,653
Awareness itself is the key.

262
00:31:41,017 --> 00:31:48,672
So there's no need to judge anger as wrong, judge greed as wrong, judge confusion or fear or anxiety as wrong.

263
00:31:49,854 --> 00:32:00,914
So long as we're maintaining awareness, our intuitive intelligence is at the ready, taking in what is happening, learning to see things as they really are.

264
00:32:04,574 --> 00:32:11,021
The last thing I want to say about the noting technique is that it fosters ongoing mindfulness.

265
00:32:12,743 --> 00:32:15,166
This is because of its link with perception.

266
00:32:16,828 --> 00:32:22,977
If we perceive something, no matter how vaguely, we naturally want to perceive it more clearly.

267
00:32:24,377 --> 00:32:25,839
Say you're looking out your window.

268
00:32:26,848 --> 00:32:31,654
You're vaguely aware of trees and bushes, but not really interested, in a bit of a daydream.

269
00:32:32,776 --> 00:32:36,540
Then a squirrel jumps from a branch, but all you see is a flash of motion.

270
00:32:37,261 --> 00:32:42,888
Suddenly you're alert, looking intently at the garden, trying to figure out what it was that caught your eye.

271
00:32:44,131 --> 00:32:46,493
This shows the stimulating power of perception.

272
00:32:47,575 --> 00:32:52,401
It's woken you up from your vague daydream, brought you into present experience.

273
00:32:54,472 --> 00:33:00,663
Now that doesn't necessarily mean you are now being mindful as you scan the garden wondering what caught your eye.

274
00:33:01,726 --> 00:33:09,259
Mostly we are so busy looking for something that we forget to register that the basic experience is one of looking, seeing.

275
00:33:12,022 --> 00:33:14,025
The same thing can happen in meditation.

276
00:33:14,766 --> 00:33:27,138
The noting gets us so interested in the detail of what we're seeing or hearing or sensing that we forget that the basic experience is one of seeing, hearing, sensing.

277
00:33:27,159 --> 00:33:29,602
For that we need to take a step back.

278
00:33:31,023 --> 00:33:36,849
Stop trying to achieve anything at all, even to see or hear or sense things in detail.

279
00:33:38,500 --> 00:33:48,989
We need to balance the stimulation provided by noting by focusing on whatever will help calm us down, become aware that we're seeing, hearing, sensing.

280
00:33:53,993 --> 00:34:00,960
For most people, the focus on the breath is naturally relaxing, but not for everyone.

281
00:34:00,980 --> 00:34:07,005
When I first started practising, a panicky feeling emerged as soon as I brought my attention to the abdomen.

282
00:34:09,331 --> 00:34:13,556
Bhante explained it as underlying fears that were manifesting on the breath.

283
00:34:14,838 --> 00:34:22,168
Once I heard that, I was delighted as it gave me a ready way to work with fear, which I already knew was undermining my life.

284
00:34:23,769 --> 00:34:27,614
But I also needed an alternative to the breath as a calming focus.

285
00:34:29,277 --> 00:34:32,440
In this case, the Mahasi recommends touching points.

286
00:34:33,001 --> 00:34:39,269
For example, focus attention on the buttocks touching the cushion, the hands on the lap.

287
00:34:41,679 --> 00:34:55,298
So, if the belly moving up and down as you breathe feels agitating rather than neutral or pleasant, then see what physical sensations would bring a degree of calm.

288
00:34:56,219 --> 00:35:01,327
The hands, the feet, the weight of the body pressing on the cushion.

289
00:35:03,210 --> 00:35:11,501
Use the noting word touching, touching, to draw attention away from thought and ground it in the body.

290
00:35:16,003 --> 00:35:21,891
Another aspect of calming the mind is to maintain mindfulness outside the meditation hall.

291
00:35:23,813 --> 00:35:27,898
Being fully present during our daily activities helps the mind to settle.

292
00:35:29,521 --> 00:35:36,048
The noting technique is a great support here as we so easily forget to be mindful outside of formal practice.

293
00:35:37,431 --> 00:35:43,057
If we get lazy and stop noting then the mind quickly runs away into daydreams and thoughts.

294
00:35:44,387 --> 00:35:54,369
Although this feels a lot easier than noting, it's only a short-term feel-good, as the mind is getting stirred up by its habitual desires and delusion.

295
00:35:55,512 --> 00:36:00,422
And that isn't calming at all, as we find when we next try to meditate.

296
00:36:05,126 --> 00:36:11,137
The Buddha likened the practice as swimming upstream against the tide of habitual desires.

297
00:36:12,059 --> 00:36:20,376
So no wonder it feels like hard work to keep noting during ordinary activities like walking to the dining room, going to the bathroom.

298
00:36:21,318 --> 00:36:27,168
Remember, we're swimming upstream, training the mind to focus on present experience.

299
00:36:30,693 --> 00:36:37,525
Another feature of the Mahasi technique that helps bring us into the here and now is to slow down.

300
00:36:39,128 --> 00:36:44,159
We walk slowly, open doors slowly, eat slowly and so on.

301
00:36:46,063 --> 00:36:52,195
The slow pace quietens the mind and develops respect for our present experience.

302
00:36:53,929 --> 00:37:06,847
Instead of rushing to the meditation hall, all legal to start meditation, we take an interest in walking slowly toward the meditation hall, already meditating, already sensitive to present experience.

303
00:37:08,909 --> 00:37:11,773
Slowing down also helps to sharpen our attention.

304
00:37:13,516 --> 00:37:17,641
We notice many little sensations in each footstep, for example.

305
00:37:19,005 --> 00:37:26,818
In turn, this extra sensitivity helps our minds to get more interested, more steady, more present.

306
00:37:29,503 --> 00:37:41,081
Both of these techniques, slowing down and noting, help us to strengthen a very powerful aspect of the Eightfold Path, conscious, intentional activity.

307
00:37:43,119 --> 00:37:49,429
Noting intentions is important because the intention behind any action sows a seed of karma.

308
00:37:51,211 --> 00:37:57,461
If we act out of greed, we reap the fruits of greed, growing ever more selfish and needy.

309
00:37:58,963 --> 00:38:07,777
If we act out of anger, we reap the fruits of anger, always ready to blame, losing friends, growing more bitter and isolated.

310
00:38:10,981 --> 00:38:14,626
Most of the time we don't notice the intention behind our actions.

311
00:38:15,487 --> 00:38:26,864
We go through our days on autopilot and so we reap the fruits of mindlessness, growing ever more entranced within our mental bubble, ever less sensitive to the reality around us.

312
00:38:28,568 --> 00:38:35,077
Here on retreat it's a time to start sensitising yourself to these many intentions that govern our future.

313
00:38:35,878 --> 00:38:37,782
Make them deliberate, considered.

314
00:38:41,304 --> 00:38:46,530
If we rush towards the meditation hall we won't notice any intentionality at all in this.

315
00:38:47,311 --> 00:38:53,197
But if we slow down we notice when we have to turn or put on our shoes and open a door.

316
00:38:54,699 --> 00:39:09,456
Each of these can then be done deliberately by first noting the intention intending to turn, then turning intending to walk, then walking intending to bend down, then bending down, so on.

317
00:39:10,668 --> 00:39:24,833
Here we're sowing the powerful kama seed of mindfulness, which is the key to waking up and living well, conscious of our impact on the world, sensitive to others and to our environment.

318
00:39:28,481 --> 00:39:34,211
The technique is a demanding one and there might be times when you feel totally fed up and discouraged.

319
00:39:35,659 --> 00:39:43,271
At those times, it's good to remember that every spiritual path is going to bring us to the edge of our comfort zone.

320
00:39:44,411 --> 00:39:47,275
That's actually the point of deepest learning.

321
00:39:49,519 --> 00:39:54,005
So, totally fed up and discouraged is the ideal setting for practice.

322
00:39:55,217 --> 00:40:01,965
If we can somehow persuade ourselves to keep at it, we will be doing ourselves a great favour in the long run.

323
00:40:03,268 --> 00:40:04,710
I do hope you succeed.

324
00:40:05,951 --> 00:40:08,775
And if you're really disheartened, come and find me.

325
00:40:09,275 --> 00:40:14,782
Talking the problem through will often help.

326
00:40:14,802 --> 00:40:19,268
In summary, it's best to think of the retreat as a training course.

327
00:40:21,172 --> 00:40:29,666
You are learning Vipassana, a meditation technique that involves a curious, open-minded scrutiny of present experience.

328
00:40:31,628 --> 00:40:44,309
This is the form of meditation developed by the Buddha and which led him to full awakening and his comprehensive picture of moral psychology which has survived 2,500 years of scrutiny.

329
00:40:47,512 --> 00:40:59,731
Vipassana trains our intuitive intelligence, an understanding of ourselves and the world we live in that is not limited by prejudices and opinions but emerges from direct experience.

330
00:41:01,072 --> 00:41:14,532
Intuitive intelligence works from the bottom up, you could say, from embodied awareness, making sense of life at the level of sensations and feelings and then feeding its understanding to the thinking mind.

331
00:41:16,824 --> 00:41:22,856
The intuitive intelligence can see through our stories and confusion, as in my sniffing example.

332
00:41:24,519 --> 00:41:29,349
Ultimately, it lets us follow the footsteps of the Buddha to full enlightenment.

333
00:41:33,798 --> 00:41:38,007
The Mahasi technique is a particular form of Vipassana training.

334
00:41:38,644 --> 00:41:42,972
It relies on attention to detail and momentary concentration.

335
00:41:44,054 --> 00:41:47,802
Whatever calls our attention becomes the focus for meditation.

336
00:41:49,403 --> 00:41:58,019
This form is particularly suited to lay people as it facilitates insight even within a relatively short timescale.

337
00:42:00,481 --> 00:42:06,277
To practice according to the Mahasi method, we use a noting word to direct attention toward present experience.

338
00:42:07,581 --> 00:42:13,900
This sharpens perception, stimulates alertness and supports mindful investigation.

339
00:42:17,170 --> 00:42:38,351
To balance these, we need to foster tranquillity, which is done by choosing a calming focus for attention, usually the breath at the abdomen or the feet while walking, by slowing down all activities to a snail's pace, and last but by no means least, maintaining mindfulness all day long.

340
00:42:40,389 --> 00:42:49,807
We also make an effort to note intentions, which fosters the choice to be mindful in daily activities rather than just lost in autopilot.

341
00:42:52,472 --> 00:43:02,331
It's a challenging technique, so we need to be prepared to feel frustrated, confused, perhaps disheartened from time to time.

342
00:43:03,610 --> 00:43:19,226
but at other times, hopefully, inspired, maybe agog with wonder, and assured that this is a valuable practice, worth going through all the pain and torture that it takes to find the path to the end of suffering.

343
00:43:21,889 --> 00:43:32,199
May your retreat be very beneficial, give you confidence that you too have the potential for full awakening, perfect peace and harmony.

